Fully Synthetic Data for Complex Surveys

Shirley Mathur Department of Statistics, B-313 Padelford Hall, University of Washington, Seattle, WA 98195-4322    Yajuan Si Survey Research Center, Institute for Social Research, University of Michigan, Rm 4014, 426 Thompson St., Ann Arbor, MI 48104    Jerome P. Reiter Department of Statistical Science, 214a Old Chemistry Building, Duke University, Durham, NC 27708-0251
Abstract

When seeking to release public use files for confidential data, statistical agencies can generate fully synthetic data. We propose an approach for making fully synthetic data from surveys collected with complex sampling designs. Specifically, we generate pseudo-populations by applying the weighted finite population Bayesian bootstrap to account for survey weights, take simple random samples from those pseudo-populations, estimate synthesis models using these simple random samples, and release simulated data drawn from the models as the public use files. We use the framework of multiple imputation to enable variance estimation using two data generation strategies. In the first, we generate multiple data sets from each simple random sample, whereas in the second, we generate a single synthetic data set from each simple random sample. We present multiple imputation combining rules for each setting. We illustrate each approach and the repeated sampling properties of the combining rules using simulation studies.

Key words: Bootstrap, Confidentiality, Disclosure, Privacy, Weights

1 Introduction

Many national statistics agencies, survey organizations, and researchers—henceforth all called agencies—disseminate microdata, i.e., data on individual units, to the public. Wide dissemination of microdata greatly benefits society, enabling broad subsets of the research community to access and analyze the collected data (Reiter, 2009). Often, however, agencies cannot release microdata as collected, because doing so could reveal survey respondents’ identities or values of sensitive attributes, thereby failing to satisfy ethical or legal requirements to protect data subjects’ confidentiality (Reiter and Raghunathan, 2007).

To manage these risks, several agencies have implemented or are considering synthetic data approaches, as first proposed by Rubin (1993). In this approach, the agency (i) randomly and independently samples units from the sampling frame to comprise each synthetic data set, (ii) imputes the unknown data values for units in the synthetic samples using models fit with the original survey data, and (iii) releases multiple versions of these data sets to the public. These are called fully synthetic data sets (Drechsler, 2011; Raghunathan, 2021). Releasing fully synthetic data can preserve confidentiality, since identification of units and their sensitive data can be difficult when the released data are not actual, collected values (Reiter and Drechsler, 2010). Methods for inferences from these multiply-imputed data files have been developed for a variety of statistical inference tasks (Raghunathan et al., 2003; Reiter, 2002, 2005a, 2005b; Drechsler and Reiter, 2010; Si and Reiter, 2011).

While prominent applications of fully synthetic data exist for censuses or administrative data (e.g., Kinney et al., 2011), many research data sets are based on surveys collected with sampling designs that use unequal selection probabilities. Previous research on multiple imputation for missing data suggests that imputation models should account for the survey design features, such as stratification, clustering, and survey weights (Reiter et al., 2006). Similarly, when using multiple imputation for synthetic data, the models also should account for the survey design (Mitra and Reiter, 2006; Fienberg, 2010). The key challenge is properly incorporating weights in the synthesis model, which relates to the long-standing debate about the role of survey weights in model-based inferences (Pfeffermann, 1993, 2011; Little, 2004).

Researchers have proposed a variety of approaches for generating fully synthetic data in complex surveys. The suggestion in early work (Rubin, 1993; Raghunathan et al., 2003; Reiter, 2002) was to take a Bayesian finite population inference approach, in which the agency (1) builds predictive models for the survey variables conditional on design features like stratum/cluster indicators or size measures, which are assumed known by the agency for every unit in the population, (2) imputes the missing survey variables for the nonsampled units in the population, and (3) takes a simple random sample from the completed population to release as one synthetic data set. A related approach uses the weighted finite population Bayesian bootstrap (WFPBB) (Dong et al., 2014), in which the agency generates completed populations by replicating individuals from the confidential data in proportion to their survey weights and then releases the completed populations, forgoing the step of simple random sampling. More recently, it has been suggested to generate synthetic weights (United Nations Economic Commission for Europe, 2022). This can be done by treating the survey weights as another variable to be synthesized, so that the agency specifies a predictive model for the weights given the other variables. Yet another suggestion is to build synthetic data models that account for the sampling design directly, so that they estimate the joint distribution of the population data. For example, the agency can use a pseudo-likelihood approach (Pfeffermann, 1993; Savitsky and Toth, 2016), in which each individual’s contribution to the likelihood function of a synthesis model is raised to a power that is a function of the survey weights (Kim et al., 2021).

Each of these methods has its potential drawbacks. The Bayesian finite population inference approach, while theoretically principled, requires completing full populations, which can be cumbersome, and the availability of design variables for all records in the population, which may not be the case in some surveys. The WFPBB releases (multiple copies of) individuals’ genuine data records, which creates obvious disclosure risks. Synthesizing weights does not have a theoretical basis; thus, it is unclear if this approach can adequately capture uncertainty from complex designs. Pseudo-likelihood approaches also may not estimate sampling variability correctly (Williams and Savitsky, 2021), and it is not clear how easily they can be implemented with machine learning synthesizers like classification and regression trees (Reiter, 2005c), which are commonly used in practical synthetic data projects (Raab et al., 2018).

In this article, we propose an approach to generating fully synthetic data from complex samples. To do so, we build on the WFPBB approach of Dong et al. (2014) by first creating pseudo-populations that account for the survey weights. We then take simple random samples (SRSs) from each pseudo-population, estimate synthesis models from each SRS, and generate draws from these models to create multiply-imputed, fully synthetic public use files. The latter step provides the confidentiality protection, as the agency is not releasing genuine records. We consider two synthetic survey data generation processes. First, we generate multiple synthetic data sets from each SRS; we call this Synrep-R. Second, we generate one synthetic data set from each SRS; we call this SynRep-1. SynRep-R releases more data sets than SynRep-1, which can result in reduced variances. However, the additional data sets can increase the overhead for the agency and secondary analysts. For both approaches, we derive multiple imputation combining rules that enable the estimation of variances. Using simulation studies, we illustrate the repeated sampling performances of the combining rules and compare them to fully synthetic data generated while disregarding the sampling design entirely.

The remainder of the article is organized as follows. Section 2 describes the two synthetic data generation processes in detail and presents the new combining rules. Section 3 presents the simulation studies. Section 4 suggests topics for future research.

2.1 Data generation process

Figure 2.1 and Figure 2.2 display the processes of generating synthetic data for SynRep-R and SynRep-1, respectively. We now describe these steps in detail.

In either process, the first step is to generate pseudo-populations using the WFPBB (Dong et al., 2014). The WFPBB generates pseudo-populations by “undoing” the complex sampling design and accounting for the sampling weights. The idea is to draw from the posterior predictive distribution of non-observed data (Yn​o​bsubscript𝑌𝑛𝑜𝑏Y_{nob}) given the observed data (Yo​b​ssubscript𝑌𝑜𝑏𝑠Y_{obs}) and the survey weights, i.e., drawing from P​(Yn​o​b∣Yo​b​s,w1,…,wn)𝑃conditionalsubscript𝑌𝑛𝑜𝑏subscript𝑌𝑜𝑏𝑠subscript𝑤1…subscript𝑤𝑛P(Y_{nob}\mid Y_{obs},w_{1},\dots,w_{n}). This distribution supposes that the population is comprised of the unique values of Yi∈𝒟subscript𝑌𝑖𝒟Y_{i}\in\mathcal{D}, and that the corresponding counts for each value in the population follow a multinomial distribution. With a non-informative Dirichlet prior distribution on the multinomial probabilities, the Pólya distribution can be used to draw the predictive samples in place of the Dirichlet-multinomial distribution.

3 Simulation Studies

We conduct simulation studies to illustrate the repeated sampling performances of the inferential methods in Section 2.2.1 and 2.2.2, estimating the finite population mean. To assist in evaluating these inferences, we also use estimates from 𝒫p​s​e​u​d​osubscript𝒫𝑝𝑠𝑒𝑢𝑑𝑜\mathcal{P}_{pseudo} and 𝒟s​r​ssubscript𝒟𝑠𝑟𝑠\mathcal{D}_{srs}. Specifically, in any simulation run, we define Pseudo-Pop as the procedure that uses a point estimator of Q¯¯𝑄\bar{Q} and variance estimator of (1+1/M)​B11𝑀𝐵(1+1/M)B computed with the WFPBB-generated pseudo-populations (𝒫(1),…,𝒫(M))superscript𝒫1…superscript𝒫𝑀(\mathcal{P}^{(1)},\dots,\mathcal{P}^{(M)}). We define Pseudo-SRS as the procedure that uses a point estimator of q¯¯𝑞\bar{q} and variance estimator of Raghunathan et al. (2003) computed with (𝒟(1),…,𝒟(M))superscript𝒟1…superscript𝒟𝑀(\mathcal{D}^{(1)},\dots,\mathcal{D}^{(M)}). As a comparison against what happens if we disregard the sampling design entirely, we define SRSsyn as the procedure that generates synthetic data by using the unweighted sample mean and standard deviation as plug-in parameters in a normal distribution, from which we draw simulated values for n𝑛n individuals. Finally, we define Direct as using the unweighted sample mean and standard deviation from 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}, i.e., ignoring the survey weights, and HT as the Horvitz and Thompson (1952) estimator and its estimated variance using 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}. We use these latter two procedures to assess the importance of accounting for the sampling design in inferences with 𝒟𝒟\mathcal{D}.

As a population, we use the Public Use Microdata Sample from the 2021 American Community Survey (ACS, 2021), comprising N=3,252,599𝑁3252599N=3,252,599 individuals. Specifically, we re-purpose the survey weights on the ACS file as a size variable, (X1,…,XN)subscript𝑋1…subscript𝑋𝑁(X_{1},\dots,X_{N}). These values range from 1 to 3,22332233,223 with a mean of 102. We generate a survey variable Yi=20+0.2​Xi+ϵisubscript𝑌𝑖200.2subscript𝑋𝑖subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑖Y_{i}=20+0.2X_{i}+\epsilon_{i}, where each ϵi∼N​(0,1002)similar-tosubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑖𝑁0superscript1002\epsilon_{i}\sim N(0,100^{2}). The resulting Y¯=40.5¯𝑌40.5\bar{Y}=40.5. From this population, we select n=1,000𝑛1000n=1,000 survey units with a probability proportional to size (PPS) sample. We set the PPS probability πi∝Xiproportional-tosubscript𝜋𝑖subscript𝑋𝑖\pi_{i}\propto X_{i} for i=1,…,N𝑖1…𝑁i=1,\ldots,N. We also perform simulation studies where we sample the n𝑛n units via a SRS, so as to check that the combining rules give reasonable answers even without unequal probabilities of selection. In each sample, we implement SynRep-R and SynRep-1 with various (M,R)𝑀𝑅(M,R) values. Specifically, we examine (M=2,R=10)formulae-sequence𝑀2𝑅10(M=2,R=10), (M=5,R=10)formulae-sequence𝑀5𝑅10(M=5,R=10), (M=10,R=10)formulae-sequence𝑀10𝑅10(M=10,R=10), (M=50,R=10)formulae-sequence𝑀50𝑅10(M=50,R=10), and (M=50,R=5)formulae-sequence𝑀50𝑅5(M=50,R=5). Code for the simulation studies is available at (GitHub address to be included in the final paper).

We repeat this process 5,000 times, drawing 5,000 independent samples of size n𝑛n and implementing the synthetic data and other methods. Let superscript s𝑠s index the results from simulation run s𝑠s. For any estimator q^^𝑞\hat{q} for any of the methods we examine, we compute the percent bias, 100​∑s=15000(q^s−Q)/(5000​Q)100superscriptsubscript𝑠15000superscript^𝑞𝑠𝑄5000𝑄100\sum_{s=1}^{5000}(\hat{q}^{s}-Q)/(5000Q). Finally, for each synthetic data method, we compute the ratios of the averages of the 5,000 values of the variance estimator to the corresponding empirical variances of the 5,000 values of q¯s​y​nssuperscriptsubscript¯𝑞𝑠𝑦𝑛𝑠\bar{q}_{syn}^{s}.

Figure 3.1 shows that Pseudo-Pop, Pseudo-SRS, SynRep-R, and SynRep-1 offer approximately unbiased point estimates across the various (M,R)𝑀𝑅(M,R) settings. All the percent bias values are less than 0.5%. The average variance estimates for the four methods are generally similar to the empirical variances, as the ratios are around 1. The values of M𝑀M mainly affect variance estimates. Larger M𝑀M allows the variance estimates to be closer to their empirical values. Similarly, increasing the value of R𝑅R improves the variance estimation under SynRep-R. However, when M=50𝑀50M=50, the results with R=5𝑅5R=5 do not differ greatly from those with R=10𝑅10R=10, which reflects the fact that inferences are based on a large number of synthetic data sets when M𝑀M is large. For all synthetic data methods, coverage rates are near the nominal 95% mark, with the smallest being near 91% when (M=10,R=10)formulae-sequence𝑀10𝑅10(M=10,R=10). In contrast, the two methods ignoring the PPS design, Direct and SRSsyn, are far from valid. They tend to have large bias (≈39absent39\approx 39%) and low coverage rates (close to 0). As expected by theory, HT results in unbiased estimates with near nominal coverage rates.

With small (M,R)𝑀𝑅(M,R) values, the combining rules in (2.2.34) and (2.2.1) do result in negative variance estimates, as evident in Table 3.1. We use the ad hoc adjustments to obtain positive variance estimates to use in constructing the confidence intervals. With M=2𝑀2M=2, many variance estimates are negative, mainly because of instability in bs​y​nsubscript𝑏𝑠𝑦𝑛b_{syn}. As M𝑀M increases, the rates of negative variance estimates decrease to the point where when M=50𝑀50M=50 all of the variance estimates are positive. We note that negative variance rates tend to be lower for SynRep-R than for SynRep-1, reflecting the benefits of increased datasets to estimate variance parameters. We also note that the negative variance rate for SynReg-R is similar to the rate for Pseudo-SRS. Evidently, when M​R𝑀𝑅MR is large, the information available in 𝒟s​y​nsubscript𝒟𝑠𝑦𝑛\mathcal{D}_{syn} to estimate bs​y​nsubscript𝑏𝑠𝑦𝑛b_{syn} is on par with the information available in 𝒟s​r​ssubscript𝒟𝑠𝑟𝑠\mathcal{D}_{srs}.

As another check of the validity of the combining rules, we repeat the simulations using a SRS in place of a PPS design. Figure 3.2 shows that when the original survey is SRS, the estimates from SynRep-R and SynRep-1 do not lose much efficiency relative to the estimators from Pseudo-SRS. The relative biases remain close to 0. The average variance estimates tend to be close to their corresponding empirical values. The coverage rates of the estimators based on Pseudo-SRS, SynRep-R, and SynRep-1 are between 0.91 and 0.94.

Overall, the simulation studies suggest that SynRep-R, and SynRep-1 can provide approximately valid inferences, and they are far superior inferentially to fully synthetic data that ignore the complex design.

4 Discussion

SynRep-R and SynRep-1 represent a general strategy for constructing fully synthetic data from complex samples: use the WFPBB to undo the complex design, then replace the confidential values with synthetic data. The multiple replicates enable variance estimation; in contrast, the variance arising from the complex design may not be accurately estimated by treating a single replicate as a simple random sample from the population. We note, however, that the WFPBB approach with M=R=1𝑀𝑅1M=R=1 still could be used to create a single synthetic data set, which may be useful in certain settings, e.g., when the synthetic data are intended for code training or exploratory analyses where variance estimation is not essential.

There are many topics related to this strategy worth further investigation. First, in practice, survey weights can be highly variable and may not be strongly related to the survey variables of interest; this can cause survey-weighted estimates to have inflated variances. This can be remedied somewhat, for example, by using model-based approaches to smooth the weights (Beaumont, 2008; Xia and Elliott, 2016; Si et al., 2020). Synthetic data generation based on the WFPBB is not immune to these weighting issues. Thus, it would be interesting to examine if and how the synthesis model can reduce the effects of variance inflation from extreme weights. Second, we focus on developing the fully synthetic data framework and corresponding combining rules, using a single finite population mean and normally distributed synthesis model to illustrate the methods. Conceptually, agencies can apply SynRep-R and SynRep-1 to multivariate data and for various estimands of interest, e.g., subdomain means and regression coefficients. In such cases, it may be advantageous to use flexible modeling approaches, such as tree-based models or other machine learning algorithms. Future work could investigate the performance of these synthesizers in combination with the pseudo-population and pseudo-SRS generation steps. Third, we derive the combining rules assuming the original survey data are complete. Agencies could impute missing survey data and generate synthetic replicates simultaneously, possibly accounting for the complex design in the imputation model and synthesis approach; this strategy may necessitate new combining rules akin to those in Reiter (2004). Fourth, negative values of the variance estimates can arise, resulting in the need for ad hoc adjustments, particularly for small M𝑀M. Future work can investigate inferential methods based on sampling from the distributions used in the derivations, as illustrated for fully synthetic data by  Si and Reiter (2011). Lastly, it would be informative to compare empirically the performances of SynRep-R and Syn-Rep-1 with those of other proposed methods for full synthesis with complex samples.
